\begin{quote}
1 Function Fitting

Machine learning is function tting. This statement might come accross as
a pejorative. An attempt to belittle the successes of machine learning.
If you think like this, think again. The capability to discover
functions describing complex data does open up amazing opportunities.
The key here is scalability towards large and complex data sets that
require functions of many variables as a descriptor. Constructing a
function of one variable, a curve describing a set of data pairs,
constitutes a feat that can impossibly be classied as earth-shattering.
However, having the capability to construct functions that describe
high-dimensional data sets containing thousands of variables does open
up com-plete new avenues. Machine learning gives us exactly that
capability. A scalable approaches for constructing functions that
describe large data sets containing lots of variables.

So we can make that rst sentence more precise: machine learning is a
scalable approach to function tting. This scalable function tting
technology attracts more and more attention, not just from computer
scientists, but also from the general public. Recent successes in
machine learning causes increasing numbers of bloggers, journalists and
other opinion makers to get carried away in depicting machine learning
as a route towards super-human intelligence. A route towards super-human
machines that runs the risk of rendering humans extinct.1Understanding
what happens \textquotesingle under the hood\textquotesingle{} of
advanced machine learning algorithms will give you a more nuanced view
on these matters. Once you have studied and digested this text, I hope
you will agree that perceiving machine learning as an existential threat
to humanity constitutes, without any doubt, an extreme form of vilifying
function tting.

There is no reason to vilify, nor to glorify, function tting. However,
as mentioned above, astonishing feats can be realized with scalable
approaches to function tting. When witnessing a machine learning
algorithm getting better at distinguishing cats from dogs in images of
pets,2our rst association is unlikely to be `function tting at
work\textquotesingle. Yet, that is in precisely what is happening:
discovering a function that maps thousands of individual pixel values
onto a binary classier (`cat\textquotesingle{} or `dog\textquotesingle).
It is dicult to imagine how, in the absence of machine learning
algorithms, one would even start constructing such a function. It is
quite amazing that with merely a database of images labelled
`cat\textquotesingle{} or `dog\textquotesingle{} as starting point, a
function tting process known as supervised machine learning accomplishes
this challenge.

Describing machine learning as function tting might suggest that the
start-ing point necessarily has to be a data set containing samples of
the function that is sought. However, such a data set need not be
available a-priori. In the absence of data, the function being sought
can be initialized at random and improved upon iteratively based on its
performance in a task that is dependent on the quality of the function.
Such so-called reinforcement learning creates ever more accurate data
while the function approximation is taking shape. This

1Nick Bostrom, Superinteligence: paths, dangers, strategies, OUP Oxford
(2014). 2https://www.kaggle.com/c/dogs-vs-cats-redux-kernels-edition
\end{quote}

5

\begin{quote}
approach has resulted in major progress in robotics,3and has also
resulted in computers crushing humans in the game of Go.4What we observe
in the latter application is a computer outperforming humans in a specic
function tting exercise. In this case the specic function being sought
is the player\textquotesingle s advantage as a function of the board
conguration. With each of the nodes on the 19 x 19 game grid
representing a separate discrete variable5in the total congura-tion, we
are dealing with a function of 361 discrete variables. A progressively
better t to this function is obtained by having multiple approximations
to this function compete against each other in Go gameplay. The result
obtained, af-ter weeks of self-training and without any domain-expert
input, appears to be super-human go-playing capabilities.

In science and engineering, machine learning provides us with an
alternative route towards constructing functions that describe a given
system. Generating system models has long been the exclusive realm of
numerical modeling. Start-ing with a system description and a theory
applicable to the physical phenomena playing a role, a numerical model
is created and implemented into a computer algorithm. For instance, in
computational uid dynamics the ow past an ob-ject (a car, the hull of a
ship, an airplane, a wind turbine, etc.) is modeled by solving the
Navier-Stokes ow equations for the geometry at hand. The numerical
results derived include parameters like drag force as function of ow
speed and as function of object geometry. These results can be compared
with experimental data, and provided a satisfactory agreement is
obtained between the two, the model can be used to predict the same
parameters for situations that lack experimental data.

What we witness in recent years is an approach being established that is
complementary to physics-based modeling. An approach that shines exactly
when traditional modeling methods struggle, and that comes to the fore
when ample data on the system\textquotesingle s behavior is available
while the system itself is too complex to be captured in a deductive
modeling exercise. This new approach of `learning\textquotesingle, as
opposed to `simulating\textquotesingle, system behaviors relies on the
func-tion tting capability of machine learning algorithms. These notes
cover this \textquotesingle machine learning approach to
modeling\textquotesingle. More specically, as the functions being sought
are generally continuous functions in the input variables provided,
throughout the text the focus is on (non-linear) regression problems (as
opposed to classication.problems).

2 About these notes

This text does not aim to be comprehensive in covering machine learning
meth-ods. Rather, it is intended to wet your appetite for machine
learning. The focus

3J.Kober, J.A. Bagnell, and J. Peters, "Reinforcement learning in
robotics: a survey", The Int. J. of Robotics Research, 32: 1238-1274
(2013).

4David Silver et al. "Mastering the game of go without human knowledge",
Nature, 550: 354359 (2017).

5Each grid point can attain three values: empty, occupied by opponent,
or occupied by self.
\end{quote}

6

\begin{quote}
is entirely on the design and training of feedforward nets (articial
neural nets) for system modeling. The type of models we will construct
are also known as surrogate models. In recent years, these ultrafast
models are seeing an increased use in high-throughput computational
screening and optimization, as well as in real-time control and
optimization.

This text is for you if your aim is to achieve a conceptual
understanding of feedforward nets and their use in science and
engineering. Emphasis is placed on key concepts that can be expected to
remain relevant, and not on specic software packages that may become
obsolete within years. If your interest is directed towards the
practicalities of machine learning software libraries, other text will
be more suitable.

The following chapters provide the reader with a look
\textquotesingle under the hood\textquotesingle{} of feedforward nets
for regression problems. Regression problems are tting prob-lems where
the function being sought is continuous.6Key concepts are intro-duced by
applying these to toy problems in regression analysis. We start with
function tting problems that can be labeled
\textquotesingle trivial\textquotesingle. For these simple problems
direct closed-form solutions exist, and machine learning represents a
roundabout (and, for the problem at hand, rather inecient) route towards
representing the function being sought. However, precisely by going
through the `overkill\textquotesingle{} of ap-plying machine learning to
these simple problems, intuitive insights and a rm grasp of the
fundamentals of machine learning algorithms become accessible.

Gradually the problems become progressively more complex, and it will
be-come intuitively clear to the reader under what circumstances
feedforward nets shine compared to traditional modeling methods. Plenty
of examples of super-vised learning tasks will be discussed, and also
reinforcement learning examples will be introduced. Throughout the text,
focus will be on feedforward nets, with network architectures ranging
from shallow (e.g. linear regression nets) to deep (e.g. deep
convolutional nets). The training methods for such nets will be
dis-cussed, with the basics of backpropagation and stochastic gradient
descent being presented in an intuitive way. By applying feedforward
nets to science-based regression problems with well dened inputs and
outputs, the reader will gain valueable insights into the strengths and
weaknesses of feedforward nets. When completing the course, you will
have an intuitive yet thorough understanding of deep learning basics.
With the knowledge gathered, you should be well-placed to start tackling
system modeling tasks using feedforward nets.

From the above it should be clear that the character of these notes are
very much those of a workbook. Machine learning is teached here as a
full-contact sport. Digesting the theoretical concepts is just the start
of the learning experience. Trying out the conceptual ideas and
algorithms in a safe training environment that provides small and
well-dened model problems renders the true and full understanding.

6As opposed to classication problems where the function being sought
takes on discrete values only.
\end{quote}

