\begin{quote}
Despite their relative arbitrariness, such yardsticks are extremely
useful pro-vided they get widely adopted. Yet, especially in the
presence of universally adopted yardsticks, we should not lose sight of
the fact that functional rela-tionships between physical measurements
should not change were one to opt for alternative yardsticks. With a
change of yardstick the gures in the relationship between physical
variables may change, yet the relationship itself should remain

7For instance, our yardstick for time, the second, is dened as the
duration of 9,192,631,770 periods of the radiation corresponding to the
transition between the two hyperne levels of the ground state of the
cesium-133 atom. The specic number 9,192,631,770 is agreed upon by
convention, and represents an accumulation of historical choices.
\end{quote}

8

