  >{\raggedright\arraybackslash}p{(\columnwidth - 4\tabcolsep) * \real{0.3333}}
  >{\raggedright\arraybackslash}p{(\columnwidth - 4\tabcolsep) * \real{0.3333}}
  >{\raggedright\arraybackslash}p{(\columnwidth - 4\tabcolsep) * \real{0.3333}}@{}}
\toprule()
\multicolumn{2}{@{}>{\raggedright\arraybackslash}p{(\columnwidth - 4\tabcolsep) * \real{0.6667} + 2\tabcolsep}}{%
\begin{minipage}[b]{\linewidth}\raggedright
\begin{quote}
invariant. In theoretical physics speak: the mathematical relationship
needs to be covariant with respect to choices of yardstick.

A basic example will make things clear. The length of the hypothenuse of
a right-angled triangle can be related to the lengths of the other two
sides via the Pythagorean relationship:
\end{quote}
\end{minipage}} &
\multirow{2}{*}{\begin{minipage}[b]{\linewidth}\raggedright
\begin{quote}
\includegraphics[width=1.45694in,height=0.89444in]{vertopal_a4c513063dc5459badc01054b1b787a4/media/image2.png}
\end{quote}
\end{minipage}} \\
\begin{minipage}[b]{\linewidth}\raggedright
\emph{c}2= \emph{a}2+ \emph{b}2
\end{minipage} & \begin{minipage}[b]{\linewidth}\raggedright
(1)
\end{minipage} \\
\midrule()
\endhead
\bottomrule()
\end{longtable}

\begin{quote}
The value of the left-hand side and right-hand side of this equation
will depend on the choice of yardstick. However, regardless whether we
measure length in meters or in inches, the relationship itself does not
change. This immediately follows from the fact that all terms on both
sides of equation (1) represent areas, and therefore carry the same
physical dimension (length squared), a property known as dimensional
homogeneity. Mathematically this boils down to the relationship
\emph{c}(\emph{a, b}) that expresses \emph{c} in terms of \emph{a} and
\emph{b}, to be homogeneous of degree 1:\\
\emph{c}(\emph{λa, λb}) = \emph{λc}(\emph{a, b}) (2)

for all \emph{λ \textgreater{}} 0. In this document we will encounter
many instances of degree-1 homogeneous functional relationships, and for
brevity we will refer to these as scaling relationships.

Here we have stumbled upon a central theme in physics: encoding
relation-ships between physical variables requires scaling relationships
in which dimen-sional homogeneity is achieved. This applies to any eort
aimed at constructing relationships between variables that describe a
given physical system. It should therefore not come as a surprise that
in this machine learning text aimed at modeling physical systems,
dimensional homogeneity and scaling relationships feature in each and
every example.

When modeling the behavior of a physical system, we work with well-dened
inputs and outputs. Dimensional homogeneity boils down to the
requirement that all inputs and all outputs are to be measured with
one-and-the-same yard-stick. In the above triangle example the uniform
yardstick took the shape of a yardstick for length. As mentioned before,
this yardstick could be a meter or it could be an inch. However, there
is still a choice to be made that goes beyond this choice. To make this
specic, imagine we don\textquotesingle t know the Pythagorean the-orem,
and based on measurement data for many right triangles we are seeking a
function that describes the length of the hypothenuse in terms of the
two other side lengths. We have to select a uniform yardstick, and it
only seems logical to opt for a yardstick of length, and to write
\emph{c} = \emph{S}(\emph{a, b}), where \emph{S}(\emph{..}) denotes the
scaling (degree-1 homogeneous) function to be determined. How-ever, we
could have chosen an entirely dierent yardstick that
deosn\textquotesingle t measure lengths. For instance, we could select
as yardstick length squared (area) and write \emph{c}2=
\emph{S}(\emph{a}2\emph{, b}2). In fact, this alternative choice of
yardstick happens to closely honor the character of the relationship
being sought, and certainly for function tting purposes this yardstick
represents a particularly ecient choice.8

8A choice that renders the hypothenuse tting problem into a trivial
exercise.
\end{quote}

9

