\begin{minipage}[b]{\linewidth}\raggedright
\begin{quote}
We will be dealing with functional relationships encoded by
computational net-works consisting of multipliers and rectiers. These
functional relationships can be expressed in algebraic notation, but
often it is more insightful to represent these in a diagram. In network
diagrams, a multiplier is represented by a solid line, and a rectier by
a wigly line. Multipliers and rectiers both come with two end points: an
input that carries an input value and an output that carries an output
value. In the diagrams, each element is always shown with its output
positioned above the input. Furthermore, a weight is associated with
each mul-tiplier. This weight represents the multiplicative value: the
ratio between the output value and the input value. In other words: a
multiplier with weight \emph{w}, when oered an input \emph{x}, will
generate an output \emph{y} = \emph{wx}. For a rectier, also referred to
as rectied linear unit (ReLU), the output equals the input, unless the
input is negative. In this latter case the output is clipped to zero. In
other
\end{quote}
\end{minipage}} \\
\midrule()
\endhead
\bottomrule()
\end{longtable}

