\begin{quote}
Given the two building blocks, we also need a rule for combining these
into functional networks. This rule is simple: the end points of
mutipliers and recti-ers can be joined together at will, thereby forming
nodes. A node that joins up several outputs acquire a value equal to the
sum of these outputs. The inputs joining up at the same node all acquire
this sum value. Note that the diagram drawing rule mentioned before "the
output of each building block is positioned above its input" not only
eliminates any ambiguity about what is the input
\end{quote}

\begin{longtable}[]{@{}
  >{\raggedright\arraybackslash}p{(\columnwidth - 2\tabcolsep) * \real{0.5000}}
  >{\raggedright\arraybackslash}p{(\columnwidth - 2\tabcolsep) * \real{0.5000}}@{}}
\toprule()
\begin{minipage}[b]{\linewidth}\raggedright
\begin{quote}
and what is the output of each element, it also prevents any `closed
computa-tional loops\textquotesingle{} to form.12Eectively, in the
diagrams a `direction of computation\textquotesingle{} emerges that is
always upward. The resulting diagrams have the input nodes at the
bottom, and the output nodes at the top. To stress the unidirectional ow
of information, these nets are referred to as feedforward nets. In these
notes we will mostly stick to this terminology. Occasionally, we will
also use the more popular and more suggestive term neural nets.

A very simple feedforward net containing just two multipliers is
represented graphically as shown on the right. The output node (the top
node in the dia-gram) yields the weighted linear sum of two input
variables \emph{x}1 and \emph{x}2 and can be expressed as \emph{y} =
\emph{w}1\emph{x}1 + \emph{w}2\emph{x}2. Such a linear network can be
extended to as many input variables as is required by the function to be
modeled: weighted linear sums of three variables can be represented with
three links joining into one node, and so on. Networks can also have
more than one output. An exam-ple is shown on the right. This network
features two inputs and three outputs, and consists of multipliers only.
The functional relationship between outputs and inputs is given by a
matrix equation:\\
 \emph{y}1 \emph{y}2 \emph{y}3 = \emph{w}11 \emph{w}21 \emph{w}31
\emph{w}12 \emph{w}22 \emph{w}32  \emph{x}1 \emph{x}2 (6)

Networks consisting exclusively of multipliers always encode a matrix
equa-tion. So any diagram of a multiplier-only net boils down to a
diagrammatic representation of a matrix equation. This also applies when
the diagram ac-quires \textquotesingle depth\textquotesingle{} with
outputs of multipliers feeding into a next layer of multipliers (see
diagram on the right). Here, the functional relationship between outputs
\end{quote}\strut
