12

\begin{quote}
and inputs is given by the matrix equation:

\emph{y}1 \emph{y}2 = \emph{v}11 \emph{v}21 \emph{v}12 \emph{v}22
\emph{v}13 \emph{v}23  \emph{w}11 \emph{w}21 \emph{w}31 \emph{w}12
\emph{w}22 \emph{w}32  \emph{x}1 \emph{x}2 (7)

Such a nested linear dependency can be contracted into a direct linear
de-pendency. This amounts to nothing more than carrying out the matrix
multi-plication in the above equation:

\includegraphics[width=3.54167in,height=2.275in]{vertopal_a4c513063dc5459badc01054b1b787a4/media/image9.png}

Note that in the contracted net the weight between a given input and a
given output takes the form of a sum over all paths that connect this
particular input-output pair in the original net. Each term in this sum
over paths is formed by a multiplication of all weights encountered
along the path considered.

By \textquotesingle freeing\textquotesingle{} the weights in the
contracted network (i.e. by not prescribing the weights to sums of
products of the weights in the nested network, but by treating all
weights as free parameters), its expressive power can not be reduced. It
follows that the expressive power of a contracted network is at least as
good as that of the original stacked network: any function that can be
expressed by adapting the weights in a nested linear network, can also
be expressed by adapting the weights in the contracted network. In the
above example, the contraction leads to a network with fewer weights (4
instead of 12) but with the same expressive power. In some cases, the
expressive power even increases by contracting linear layers. In the
diagram below, the contraction leads to a network with fewer weights (9
instead of 12) and increased expressive power: modifying the 9 weights
in the diagram at the right leads to richer input-output relationships
than modifying the 12 weights in the diagram on the left.
\end{quote}

13

