\begin{quote}
diagram with two inputs represents the functional relationship \emph{y}
= \emph{g}(\emph{w}1\emph{x}1 + \emph{w}2\emph{x}2). Such a functional
relationship loosely mimics the signals propagating through biological
neurons. For that reason a feedforward net like the one depicted on the
right is often referred to as an articial neuron. Note that in this
diagram, we have suppressed listing the weights. This is useful when
discussing generic functional relationships. Throughout the text, in
case the weights take specic values, these will be listed explicitly in
the relevant diagrams.

A more complex network is shown below. The functional relation
represented by this graph can be written as:

\emph{y} = \emph{w}01\emph{g}(\emph{w}11\emph{x}1 + \emph{w}12\emph{x}2)
+ \emph{w}02\emph{g}(\emph{w}21\emph{x}1 + \emph{w}22\emph{x}2) +
\emph{w}03\emph{g}(\emph{w}31\emph{x}1 + \emph{w}32\emph{x}2) (8)
\end{quote}

\includegraphics[width=1.18056in,height=2.01805in]{vertopal_a4c513063dc5459badc01054b1b787a4/media/image12.png}

\begin{quote}
Computational nets of much higher complexity can be created. Often, such
nets follow a layered architecture consisting of alternating layers of
multipliers
\end{quote}

14

\begin{quote}
(straight lines) and layers of rectiers (wiggly lines). The
unidirectional in-formation ow in such layered nets becomes pronounced
when considering the computation of the nodal values. Once the inputs
(the bottom row of nodes) are specied, the values of the nodes one level
up in the diagram directly follow. Via iteration the nodal values in
higher layers follow. This iterative computa-tion is complete once the
values for the top nodes (the output nodes) have been computed. This
bottom-up computational proces is referred to as a forward pass through
the network. Later we will also encounter a backward pass (the so-called
backpropagation) used in the updating of the weights of the net (the
training of the net).

Alternating layers of multipliers and rectiers prevents multipliers
feeding directly into multipliers. This ensures that the net can not be
contracted in the way indicated above. In machine learning literature,
feedforward nets contain alternating linear and non-linear layers are
often represented diagrammatically in more course-grained ways. A
double-layer consisting of weighted linear sums feeding into rectiers is
typically represented as a single layer of articial neu-rons. Each layer
of output nodes of these articial neurons that acts as inputs for a next
layer of articial neurons, is referred to as a layer of hidden nodes.
Following this convention, below diagram contains two layers of hidden
nodes (indicated in black).
\end{quote}

\includegraphics[width=1.225in,height=2.93194in]{vertopal_a4c513063dc5459badc01054b1b787a4/media/image13.png}

\begin{quote}
The adaptive weights of the feedforward net are associated with the
linear layers. An important parameter for these nets is therefore the
number of linear layers that is present, a parameter commonly referred
to as the depth of the net. Alternatively, as the number of linear
layers always exceeds the number of layers of hidden nodes by one, the
depth can also be expressed as the number of hidden layers. When
represented as a functional relation, the depth of nesting of the
non-linear transforms corresponds to the depth of the net expressed in
number
\end{quote}

15

\begin{quote}
of hidden layers. As an example, the feedforward net depicted above has
two layers of hidden nodes and therefore three linear layers with
adaptive weights. This diagram corresponds to a functional nestings of
the form \emph{w}0\emph{g}(\emph{w}01\emph{g}(\emph{w}11\emph{x}1+
\emph{w}12\emph{x}2) + \emph{..}).
\end{quote}

