straight line to your starting point. This return journey takes \emph{d}
steps. You note down the triplet (\emph{n, m, d}) and repeat the
experiment for dierent \emph{n} and \emph{m} values. This results in two
dozen triplets all noted down in the table on the right. The question
is: based on this data, can you predict for arbitrary values of \emph{n}
and \emph{m} the number of steps \emph{d} that will bring you in a
straight line back to your starting point? Can you do so within an
accuracy of 1\%?

We are seeking a function \emph{f}() such that \emph{d} =
\emph{f}(\emph{n, m}). As mentioned: we assume a complete lack of
knowledge of the Pythagorean theorem. Still it helps to consider the
general characteristics of the function \emph{f}(). We might not be
familiar with the Pythagorean theorem, but that surely
doesn\textquotesingle t mean we have zero knowledge about this function.

Firstly, we notice that the function \emph{f}(\emph{n, m}) is symmetric
in it\textquotesingle s arguments:
