\begin{quote}
Another way of noting down this expression is \emph{d} =
\emph{f}(\emph{max}(\emph{n, m})\emph{, min}(\emph{n, m})). Henceforth,
without loss of generality, we assume \emph{n ≥m} and write \emph{d} =
\emph{f}(\emph{n, m}).
\end{quote}

16

\begin{quote}
A second symmetry applies. This symmetry is the scaling symmetry
dis-cussed in section 3. Physics principles dictate the relationship
\emph{d} = \emph{f}(\emph{n, m}) to be invariant under the choice of
unit of length. For instance, if the relationship \emph{d} =
\emph{f}(\emph{n, m}) is obtained for a certain step size, then the very
same relationship must hold when the step size is halved. It follows
that 2\emph{d} = \emph{f}(2\emph{n,} 2\emph{m}). More in general, if
\emph{d} = \emph{f}(\emph{n, m}), then for any positive value of
\emph{λ} it must also be true that \emph{λd} = \emph{f}(\emph{λn, λm}).
In math lingo: the function \emph{f}() must be a homogeneous function of
degree one: \emph{f}(\emph{λn, λm}) = \emph{λf}(\emph{n, m}). Here we
refer to such functions as scaling functions.

We can further benet from the freedom we have in choosing units. There
is no need to select your step size as unit of measurement. Within a
single data triplet we should avoid mixing units, but we do have the
freedom to select the unit of length for each input data triplet
separately. More specically, as long as we restrict ourselves to scaling
tting functions\emph{f}(\emph{n, m}), we can select the unit of length
for each input data triplet equal to the length of the return journey.
This renders the third value in each of the data triplets equal to
unity.

Incorporating the north-east permutation symmetry as well as the scale
sym-metry, it follows that we can limit ourselves to the twelve
re-scaled input data points shown below.
\end{quote}

