\emph{φ}(\emph{w}1\emph{x} + \emph{w}2\emph{y}). In the above exercise
we have used for the transfer funstion \emph{φ}() the identity
function\emph{φ}(\emph{z}) = \emph{z}, but we could have used any
degree-1 homogeneous function. As long as \emph{φ}(\emph{λz}) =
\emph{λφ}(\emph{z}) for all positive \emph{λ}, scaling symmetry for
\emph{f}() will be honoured. A suitable transfer function is the rectier
function \emph{g}(\emph{z}) = \emph{max}(\emph{z,} 0) that was
introduced in section 4. In contrast to the identity function, this
choice of transfer function results in a tting term
\emph{g}(\emph{w}1\emph{x}+\emph{w}2\emph{y}) that makes the
construction of a sum of such terms meaningful as a tting function. Thus
we land on an expansion of the form
