\begin{quote}
The blue tting curve in above x-y plot consists of two linear segments.
In general, an approximation based on a feedforward net with ReLUs is
piecewise linear, with the number of linear regions corresponding to the
complexity of the net. Having accomplished a robust t to the return
distances, we will not pursue eorts aimed at improving the t by
increasing the number of linear regions.

We do note however, that if needed, we can systematically increase the
number of linear regions by expanding the feedforward net. One way is to
increase the width of the feedforward net by including additonal tting
terms. E.g. by using \emph{f}(\emph{x, y}) =
\emph{g}(\emph{w}11\emph{x}+\emph{w}12\emph{y})+\emph{g}(\emph{w}21\emph{x}+\emph{w}22\emph{y})+\emph{g}(\emph{w}31\emph{x}+\emph{w}32\emph{y}).
Alternatively, we can increase the depth of the network. This boils down
to the use of nested tting functions containing terms like
\emph{g}(\emph{w}01\emph{g}(\emph{w}11\emph{x} + \emph{w}12\emph{y}) +
\emph{w}02\emph{g}(\emph{w}21\emph{x}+\emph{w}22\emph{y})). A prominent
current trend in machine learning research is the use of deep nestings,
i.e.\\
the use of deep feedforward nets. This approach is referred to as deep
