\midrule()
\endhead
\bottomrule()
\end{longtable}

\begin{quote}
The euclidian distance exercise in previous sections made us land two
alternative function tting approaches. Each approach implies a dierent
philosophy to function tting. Let\textquotesingle s investigate this in
more detail.

The rst method, linear regression, approximates a function
\emph{f}(\emph{x, y}) using an expansion of the form

\emph{f}(\emph{x, y}) = \emph{w}1\emph{g}1(\emph{x, y}) +
\emph{w}2\emph{g}2(\emph{x, y}) + \emph{w}3\emph{g}3(\emph{x, y}) +
\emph{..} (13)

Here, the various basis functions \emph{gk}(\emph{x, y}) used in the
expansion function are all fully specied by the user. These basis
functions do depend on the input variables \emph{x} and \emph{y}, and in
general they do so in a non-linear fashion, but they
don\textquotesingle t depend on any tting parameters. The function
\emph{f} does depend on the tting parameters \emph{\{wk\}}, and does so
in the form of a linear dependency. For function tting problems where a
suitable set of basis functions is available, linear regression provides
us with a convenient function tting method.

The second method, feedforward net based regression, in its most basic
form approximates a function \emph{f}(\emph{x, y}) by using an expansion
of the form

\emph{f}(\emph{x, y}) = \emph{g}(\emph{w}11\emph{x} +
\emph{w}12\emph{y}) + \emph{g}(\emph{w}21\emph{x}+\emph{w}22\emph{y}) +
\emph{...} (14)

where the function \emph{g}() denotes a rectier function. In more
complex cases, a nesting of such rectier functions appears:

\emph{f}(\emph{x, y}) = \emph{g}(\emph{w}01\emph{g}(\emph{w}11\emph{x} +
\emph{w}12\emph{y}) +
\emph{w}02\emph{g}(\emph{w}21\emph{x}+\emph{w}22\emph{y})) + \emph{...}
(15)

Apart from the choice of nesting (the
\textquotesingle architecture\textquotesingle{} of the feedforward net),
the user does not need to make any eorts in identifying suitable basis
functions nor in identifying any other form of representation underlying
the tting problem.

Both in linear regression as well as in non-linear feedforward net
regression, we need to make a choice of coordinates used to represent
the input. In the above equations this is the choice of the coordinates
\emph{x} and \emph{y}. This often boils down to a choice for a suitable
uniform yardstick (see chapter 3). Given the choice of coordinates, the
routes subsequently followed in linear regression and in feedforward net
regression depart sharply. In loose terms, the linear regression
\end{quote}

22

\begin{quote}
route relies on a tting process with hand-designed representations in
the chosen coordinates, while the non-linear feedforward net method
discovers itself the representation in terms of the coordinates. For
this reason the feedforward net based method is sometimes referred to as
representation learning. In recent years, the term deep learning has
become more common. Here, the adjective
\textquotesingle deep\textquotesingle{} refers to the depth of
functional nesting that tends to be employed.

Deep feedforward nets enable the discovery of nested representations:
high-level representations in the form of patterns of nodal values,
expressed in ever simpler representations, until the most basic
representations are reached: pat-terns of nodal values that depend
directly on the values of the input layer (the chosen coordinates). The
current hype surrounding machine learning can be traced back to the
success of deep networks in applications such as handwritten character
recognition and speech recognition. These are areas where, despite
decades of research, hand-designed representations and rule-based
feature de-tection have failed to deliver success.

9 Review problem: water waves

We are all familiar with water waves occurring at the air-sea interface
of oceans. In physics these waves are referred to as surface gravity
waves, a terminology that stresses the fact that the restoration of the
uid interface to equilibrium is due to gravity. For small amplitudes,
that is for wave amplitudes small in comparison to the wavelength and
small in comparison to the water depth, the propagation velocity of the
water waves becomes independent of the amplitude. For large-scale waves
occurring at ocean-air interfaces, also surface tension ef-fects and
viscous eects can be neglected. The result is that propagation speed (or
celerity) \emph{c} of these water waves depends only on the water depth
\emph{h}, the wavelength \emph{λ}, and the gravitational acceleration
\emph{g}. Below table lists some prop-agation speeds as function of
water depth and wavelength. All units are SI units. The gravitational
acceleration equals 9\emph{.}8m\emph{/}s2.
\end{quote}

