\begin{quote}
So far we have specied feedforward nets via their architecture and their
weights. These weights are associated with each of the multipliers, the
straight line seg-ments in the network diagrams. In literature on
feedforward nets you will typi-cally come across additional tting
parameters, the so-called biases. These bias parameters can be thought
of as being associated with the rectiers, the wavy links in the network
diagrams. For an articial neuron that receives inputs \emph{x}1 and
\emph{x}2 with weights \emph{w}1 and \emph{w}2, respectively, a bias
\emph{w}0 has the eect to produce an output \emph{g}(\emph{w}1\emph{x}1
+\emph{w}2\emph{x}2 +\emph{w}0). Such a non-zero bias can be represented
via an additional link with weight equal to the bias that feeds in an
additional input with value unity. (See diagram on the right.)
Throughout this text, whenever we need non-zero biases, we will do so by
including \textquotesingle unit inputs\textquotesingle.14
\end{quote}
\end{minipage}} \\
\midrule()
\endhead
\bottomrule()
\end{longtable}

\begin{quote}
Bias parameters are generally a necessity when modeling functional
relation-ships that are heuristic in nature. Losely speaking, the need
for bias parameters in heuristic models indicate eects not explicitely
considered and modelled as a \textquotesingle background
contribution\textquotesingle. In other words, under these conditions the
need for bias parameters suggests one (or more) input parameters to be
missing.

However, also in scientic modeling exercises the need for a bias
parameter can manifest itself. This is usually the case when the
modeling exercise utilizes dimensionless parameters. Eectively, in such
cases the bias parameter that

14In the Euclidean distance exercise no biases were required. Non-zero
bias parameters are required, however, if the function being modeled
fails to observe scale invariance.
\end{quote}

24

\begin{quote}
is required represents an input parameter that is utilized as natural
yardstick for rendering the scaling relation dimensionless. For
instance, in the Euclidian distance exercise a bias parameter emerges
when rendering the scaling relation \emph{d} = \emph{f}(\emph{n, m})
dimensionless by measuring all distances in terms of \emph{n}, the
larger of the two input distances: \emph{n}= \emph{f}(1\emph{,\sout{m}
n}). Here the dependency on the rst argument of the function \emph{f}()
manifests itself as a bias input. Of course one can write: \emph{n}=
\emph{f}(\emph{\sout{m} n}), but in that case an auxilary unit input
parameter (a bias parameter) need to be introduced when modeling the
functional dependence of \emph{n}on\emph{\sout{m} n}.

In applications where all inputs and outputs are presented in
dimensionally homogeneous form (i.e. all expressed in terms of the same
\textquotesingle yardstick\textquotesingle, as was the case in the
Euclidian distance example), bias parameters are unwanted. The learning
examples in this text are all best solved with ReLU nets operating on
dimensionally homogeneous inputs, and void of any bias parameters.

11 Expressive power

Feedforward nets with hidden layers give us a universal approximation
capabil-ity. More specically, the universal approximation
theorem15states that every continuous function on a given domain can be
approximated to any required degree of accuracy by a feedforward net
with at least one hidden layer. This result holds for a wide range of
activation functions that include the ReLUs used throughout this text.16
The universal approximation theorem is non-constructive: it states that
regardless the complexity of a function, a su-ciently large feedforward
net containing at least one hidden layer can represent this function.
However, it does not state how to arrive at such a representa-tion. The
following sections will deal with the key question of how to arrive at
the weights that make a feedforward net a suitable approximation to a
given function.

For functions of one variable, the universal approximation theorem can
be understood intuitively by considering feedforward ReLU nets with a
single hid-den layer as shown below.

15K. Hornik, M. Stinchcombe, and H. White, "Multilayer feedforward
networks are universal approximators", Neural Networks Vol. 2, 359 - 366
(1989). G. Cybenko, "Approximation by superpositions of a sigmoidal
function", Mathematics of Control, Signals and Systems Vol. 2, 303 - 314
(1989).

16M. Leshno, V.Y. Lin, A. Pinkus, and S. Schocken, "Multilayer
feedforward networks with a nonpolynomial activation function can
approximate any function", Neural Networks Vol. 6, 861 -867 (1993).
\end{quote}

25

\includegraphics[width=4.41667in,height=2.58333in]{vertopal_a4c513063dc5459badc01054b1b787a4/media/image22.png}

\begin{quote}
Firstly, from this picture it should be clear that with a single layer
of hid-den nodes any piecewise linear continuous function of one
variable can be con-structed, provided a sucient number of hidden nodes
is implemented. Here the general rule is that the implementation of
\emph{N} kinks in the piecewise linear function requires \emph{N} hidden
nodes (the case \emph{N} = 2 is shown in above picture). Secondly, to
approximate any given function to a specied level of accuracy translates
into a piecewise linear function with a specied minimum number of linear
regions (i.e. a sucient number of kinks). The two statements combined
form the bare essence of the universal approximation theorem for
functions of a single variable. Similar considerations apply when
considering functions depen-dent on multiple variables.

In summary, the universal approximation theorem tells us that given a
func-tion, there exist feedforward nets large enough to achieve any
desired level of accuracy in approximating this function. However, the
theorem doesn\textquotesingle t tell us how large these nets will be. If
we restrict ourselves to a single layer of hid-den nodes, depending on
the function to be approximated, we might need an excessive number of
hidden nodes. For single-hidden-layer feedforward ReLU nets modeling
functions of a single variable, this follows from the fact that
dou-bling the number of linear regions requires a doubling of the width
of the net. On the other hand, the same doubling of the number of linear
regions can also be achieved by adding a hidden layer consisting of just
two nodes.17Hence, a deeper net can simulate functions that would
require exponentially more re-sources (exponentially more nodes and
weights) when implemented as a shallow net. In crude terms, the improved
representation power of deeper nets results from the deep hierarchical
composition of the approximation function allowed by deep networks. In
other words, a deep architecture allows the function to be learned to
consists of a hierarchy of computations where the result of each
computation feeds into a higher level computation, until the nal output
is

17G.F. Montufar, R. Pascanu, K. Cho, and Y. Bengio, "On the number of
linear regions of deep neural networks", NIPS (2014).
\end{quote}

26

\begin{quote}
reached.

The fact that deeper models tend to perform better is therefore not
really dierent from the benets brought by using hierarchical
computations in any computational models: allowing for the re-use of
low-level computations creates eciency in code complexity. Practical
experience with a variety of architec-tures on a wide variety of
functional approximation tasks conrms that going from shallow to deeper
nets, when done in the right way, results in better ap-proximations.

12 Quantifying model performance

In the Euclidian distance learning example we manually changed the
weights \textbf{w} and tracked the accuracy of the t by visual
inspection of a plot comprising all relevant dimensions in data space.
This worked ne for that particular problem where the relevant data space
consisted of only two dimensions. In the following we will be dealing
with data spaces containing many more dimensions, and for such problems
the approach of graphically tracking the accuracy of the t breaks down
completely. Therefore, we will be using approaches for function tting
that do not rely on visual inspections, and that can be automated. These
approaches require a well-dened measure for function tting performance.

The performance of a model in approximating a continuous function is
con-veniently measured by the square errors of each of the modelled data
points. For data point \emph{i} this square error is determined by the
dierence between the modeled value \emph{f}(\emph{i}) \emph{N}, i.e. the
value of the output node \emph{N} on the input \textbf{x}(\emph{i}), and
the target value \emph{t}(\emph{i}) \emph{N}as follows:

\emph{E}(\emph{i})= 1 2 \emph{f}(\emph{i}) \emph{N−t}(\emph{i}) (16)\\
2

Here, the factor1\emph{/}2 is included for convenience.

For function tting problems where the target values cover a large
dynamic range, and where a tting function with a small relative error is
sought, it is generally advantageous to weight the square error (16)
with the inverse of the square of the target value. This results in a
relative square error metric
