\begin{quote}
\includegraphics[width=5.05in,height=4.49444in]{vertopal_a4c513063dc5459badc01054b1b787a4/media/image23.png}

The capacity of a model measures its ability to t a wide variety of
functions. The capacity of a feedforward net is dependent on its
architecture. In general, the capacity of a feedforward net increases
with increasing depth and increasing width. Also increasing the density
of connects between subsequent layers tends to increase the capacity of
the net. An alternative means to control the capacity of a model (a
feedforward net, or any other model) is achieved by regularizing the
model. In the widest sense, regularization involves all measures aimed
at reducing the gap between test error and training error. In this text
we will not study regularization in detail, but in each of the practical
examples that follow in this text, we will work hard to minimize the
training error, while avoiding a gap between the test error and the
training error to develop.

