\begin{quote}
greatest ascent). The multiplier \emph{µ} is known as the learning rate.
This learning rate needs to be selected small enough to prevent
instabilities in the training process, and large enough to avoid an
excessive number of iterations towards the minimum training error.

For small enough learning rates, the above gradient descent algorithm
will converge to \textbf{w}-values for which the
gradient\emph{\uline{∂Etrain}∂}\textbf{w} vanishes. This means that the
above gradient descent algorithm will land us in a (local) minimum or in
a saddlepoint. A (local) maximum can be excluded as the direction from
which we have arrived at this particular point provides us with a
direction in which the training error increases. Being in a local
minimum would require walking away in any of the directions to lead to
training error increases. Being in a saddle point would require no more
than one direction in which the treaining error increases. In
high-dimensional \textbf{w}-spaces, we therefore expect saddlepoints to
occur much more frequently than local minima.

The good news is that getting stuck in a saddlepoint can be avoided by
incorporating a stochastic component in the gradient descent algorithm.
The idea here is that such a stochastic component will prevent the
iteration pro-cess \textquotesingle to freeze\textquotesingle{} on a
saddle point, and rather to be \textquotesingle shaken
into\textquotesingle{} directions from which paths towards further
descent open up. Adding stochasticity to the learning process is
conveniently done by sub-sampling the training error. In the most
extreme case, these subsamples constitute individual data points. In
other \emph{∂}\textbf{w}values have words, for making updates to the
weights we don\textquotesingle t wait till
all\emph{\uline{∂E}}(\emph{i}) been computed (see Eq. 18), but rather we
make an update every time a new\emph{\uline{∂E}}(\emph{i})
\emph{∂}\textbf{w} becomes available:\\
∆\textbf{w}(i)= \emph{−µ∂E}(\emph{i}) (19)

Typically, the order in which the samples \emph{i} are selected follows
from a simple loop through a shued training set. One pass through the
entire data set is referred to as a training epoch. At the start of each
epoch the training set gets reshued.

To build an intuition on gradient descent versus stochastic gradient
descent, we revisit the linear regression treatment of the Euclidian
distance problem (see section 5). For this problem, the training error
