\begin{quote}
algorithms create paths from red to blue in above 2D color maps. These
paths are created by an iteration of small steps each of which is taken
following the color gradient. The gradient descent algorithm creates a
sequence of step from red to blue in the color map at the bottom. The
stochastic gradient descent corresponds to a sequence of steps, with
each color-gradient step executed based on either the top-left or
top-right color map, where the choices between the left and right map is
made at random.
\end{quote}

31

\begin{quote}
For feedforward nets more complex than a linear regression net with only
two links, creating a color landscape for gradient descent would involve
an unwieldy high-dimensional map (one dimension for each link with
associated weight pa-rameter). This would not be very useful and neither
would it be very instructive. Fortunately, we don\textquotesingle t need
such a high-dimensional map, as the gradients in theérror landscape can
be computed directly in a very ecient way. This is the subject of the
next section.

14 Backpropagation

