\begin{quote}
feedforward nets

The combination of Eqs. (23), (24), (26), and (27) captures the full
backpropagation-enabled stochastic gradient descent algorithm.

Based on the material discussed so far, the following list of steps
emerges as a useful recipe for regression with feedforward nets:
\end{quote}

33

\begin{quote}
Step 1: For the problem at hand: determine a complete set of input
variables and output variable(s). The set is complete when all inputs
are included that are required to (at least in principle) determine the
output.

Step 2: Use dimensional analysis to cast input and output data in
dimensionally homogeneous form (e.g. inputs and outputs all expressed as
a length). When done, you have selected the homogeneous coordinates in
which the poblem is to be described, and your regression problem is
suitable to be attacked by a feedforward net free of bias parameters and
utilising simple ReLU transforms as non-linear elements.

Step 3: Study the symmetries that apply: which transformations of the
inputs leaves the output(s) invariant? As we saw in the Euclidian
distance exercise, often the output is invariant under permutations of
(some of) the inputs. Aim to redene your inputs such that the
invariances observed become \textquotesingle hard wired\textquotesingle.

Step 4: Check the available data. Is the data complete: does every
output come with a complete set of inputs? Clean up the data where
required. Taking into account the symmetries discovered in step 3), is
the data that is left suciently rich to attempt a regression exercise?
Seek more data if the answer is \textquotesingle no\textquotesingle.

Step 5: Split the data in a training set and a test set.
\end{quote}

\begin{longtable}[]{@{}
  >{\raggedright\arraybackslash}p{(\columnwidth - 4\tabcolsep) * \real{0.3333}}
  >{\raggedright\arraybackslash}p{(\columnwidth - 4\tabcolsep) * \real{0.3333}}
  >{\raggedright\arraybackslash}p{(\columnwidth - 4\tabcolsep) * \real{0.3333}}@{}}
\toprule()
\begin{minipage}[b]{\linewidth}\raggedright
