18 Temporal dierence training

In all previous chapters, we have limited ourselves to weight updating
via su-pervised learning. For each instance of input data a desired
output value was available, and the network weights got iteratively
updated so as to reproduce at the output the desired values for each of
the various inputs. One can think of the desired output value for each
of the input samples as a target value provided by an oracle. The oracle
providing target values can be experimentation and/or physics-based
simulation.

However, in many applications an oracle is not available. An example
be-ing the evaluation of board positions in games like chess and Go. Can
we, in the absence of an oracle, still make meaningful updates to the
net and thereby train it for the use in evaluating board positions? To
make improvements to the weights using gradient descent methods, we need
target values for the output node(s). Intuitively it should be clear
that we don\textquotesingle t really need perfect tar-get values. All
that is needed at each stage of the iterative training is target values
that provide an improvement compared to the output values computed by
the network. Temporal dierence learning provides a framework for such a
weights update strategy. Temporal dierence learning has been used by
Google DeepMind in realising their super-human Go-playing neural net.
This learning method is based on a bootstrapping mechanism21that can be
summarized as "improving your guess based on a later guess". It can be
interpreted as a su-pervised learning process in which the target value
for a prediction is a later prediction presumed to be closer to the
truth. Here we deal with temporal dif-ference learning dened in a wider
context, where a so-called renormalization ow takes the role of temporal
evolution.

The key idea common to any renormalization process is the fact that
while most physical systems are characterized by many parameters, we
seldomly are interested in each and every parameter. Often our interest
focusses on a few or just a single parameter(s). Obviously, multiple
parameter settings will lead to the exact same value for the
parameter(s) of interest. In renormalization

21"Bootstrapping" or "pulling oneself up by one\textquotesingle s
bootstraps": achieving an action that seems impossible without invoking
additional resources.
\end{quote}

38

\begin{quote}
approaches one seeks transformations in parameter space that leaves the
pa-rameter(s) of interest invariant. The paths in parameter space traced
out under such renormalization transformations are referred to as
renormalization ows. Knowledge of such renormalization ows enables
temporal-dierence type learn-ing.22Renormalization represent a powerful
concept for theoretical and numeri-cal analysis in many areas of
physics. Renormalization ows are often the result of a coarse-graining
(upscaling) transformation in parameter space. However, this need not be
the case, and what is a suitable renormalization transformation will
very much depend on the details of the problem at hand. To clarify the
core idea, we look at a very simple example.

Consider the following alternating series:
