\begin{quote}
These are all slowly converging. The question arises if we could
estimate the sums of such series based on just the rst terms. To do so
we write the general series:\\
\emph{S} = \emph{a}0 + \emph{a}1 + \emph{a}2 + \emph{a}3 + \emph{· · ·}
(32)

where subsequent \emph{ak}\textquotesingle s are constrained to have
alternating signs: \emph{akak}+1 \emph{\textless{}} 0 for all \emph{k} =
0\emph{,} 1\emph{,} 2\emph{, · · ·} . We dene the remainder \emph{R}
after \emph{k} terms, and write:

\emph{S} = \emph{a}0 + \emph{a}1 + \emph{· · ·} + \emph{ak−}2 +
\emph{ak−}1 + \emph{R}(\emph{ak, ak}+1\emph{, · · ·} ) (33)

A natural \textquotesingle renormalization
transformation\textquotesingle{} presents itself: reduce the number of
terms in the partial sum by reducing \emph{k} to \emph{k −}1 in the
above expression:

\emph{S} = \emph{a}0 + \emph{a}1 + \emph{· · ·} + \emph{ak−}2 +
\emph{R}(\emph{ak−}1\emph{, ak, · · ·} ) (34)

We conclude that

\emph{R}(\emph{ak−}1\emph{, ak, · · ·} ) = \emph{ak−}1 +
\emph{R}(\emph{ak, ak}+1\emph{, · · ·} ) (35)

We now make the bold approximation that the remainder \emph{R} can be
estimated based on retaining only its rst two arguments:23
