we happen to have rediscovered Euler transforms as an acceleration
technique for summing alternating series.

19 Once more: pendulum frequency

In section 16 we created small networks for the prediction of pendulum
frequen-cies for large-amplitude oscillations. Starting point consisted
of a data set of accurate pendulum frequencies. What if such a data set
is not available? Can we use some form of TD learning to train networks
in predicting pendulum frequencies? This indeed is the case. Key point
again is to note is that our interest focuses on just a single
parameter, the oscillation frequency. Multiple input pairs
(\emph{ω}+\emph{,ω−}) will yield the same oscillation frequency
\emph{ω}. This is made explicit in below gure.

26Note that although both results agree down to the fourth digit, the
agreement with the innite sum, \emph{π/}4 = 0\emph{.}7854, does not go
further than the second digit. This once more is an indication of the
very slow convergence of this series.
\end{quote}

41

\begin{quote}
\includegraphics[width=4.39167in,height=2.73333in]{vertopal_a4c513063dc5459badc01054b1b787a4/media/image33.png}

same pendulum frequency. The existence of such
\textquotesingle equi-frequency curves\textquotesingle{} is in Here the
curves with arrowheads connect points in \emph{ω}+\emph{−ω−}space with
the

itself far from remarkable. What is remarkable, however, is the fact
that a straigthforward prescription exists for adjusting pendulum
parameters in such a way that the pendulum frequency remains unchanged.
Iterating this prescrip-tion causes a walk along the equi-frequency
curves in the directions indicated by the arrowheads. This walk along
equi-frequency paths can be interpreted as an example of a
renormalization ow. The renormalization ow for pendulum frequencies
hinges on an expression of pendulum frequencies in terms of elliptic
integrals, and goes back to the early work on elliptic integrals by
Lagrange and Gauss.

Without going into details of the derivation,27we present the
transforma-tions that leave the pendulum frequency unchanged. These
transformations are particularly elegant when expressed in terms of in
\emph{ω}+ and \emph{ω−}:
