\begin{quote}
Once \emph{θt}+1 has been computed, the discretized angular velocity
∆\emph{t}+1 :=\emph{θt}+1 \emph{−θt} immediately follows. The problem
statement is now: given \emph{θt} and ∆\emph{t}, which acceleration
\emph{at} should be applied in order to optimize the balancing of the
pendulum? As performance measure we introduce the cost-to-go:

\emph{C} (\emph{θt, θt}+1\emph{, · · ·} ) = (1 \emph{−cosθt}) + \emph{γ}
(1 \emph{−cosθt}+1) + \emph{γ}2(1 \emph{−cosθt}+2) + \emph{· · ·} (42)

Here 0 \emph{\textless{} γ} ⩽1 represents a xed discount factor. The use
of a discount factor smaller than unity implies that we are focused on
what happens next and that we are less concerned about the performance
in a more distant future. Regardless the precise value of the discount
factor \emph{γ}, the cost-to-go \emph{C} vanishes
\end{quote}

45

\begin{quote}
if-and-only-if the angle \emph{θ} vanishes from discrete time \emph{t}
onward, i.e. when the pendulum is standing still in inverted position.

Instead of evaluating the innite sum (42), we can also write the
cost-to-go in the form of a recurrence equation:

\emph{C} (\emph{θt, θt}+1\emph{, · · ·} ) = (1 \emph{−cosθt}) +
\emph{γC} (\emph{θt}+1\emph{, θt}+2\emph{, · · ·} ) (43)

this so-called Bellman equation is similar to the renormalization
equation (35), and we can follow the same approach as in section 18 to
translate this recur-rence equation into a training strategy for a
feedforward net modeling the cost function. To do so, we rst note that
future pendulum angles \emph{θt′} depend on the current pendulum angle
\emph{θt}, the current angular velocity \emph{∆t}, and the currently
applied acceleration \emph{at}, and we re-write the Bellman equation
(43) as

\emph{C} (\emph{θt,} ∆\emph{t, at}) = (1 \emph{−cosθt}) + \emph{γC}
(\emph{θt}+1\emph{,} ∆\emph{t}+1\emph{, at}+1) (44)

We can interpret this equation as a xed-point equation and use it to
train a feedforward net rendering an approximation \emph{C} (\emph{θ,}
∆\emph{, a}). This works as fol-lows: rst a discount factor gets
selected (e.g. \emph{γ} = 0\emph{.}9), and a feedforward net
approximating \emph{C} (\emph{θ,} ∆\emph{, a})gets initialized. Then the
following six steps are iterated:

Step 1: Using the feedforward net as estimator for the cost \emph{C},
for given \emph{θt} and∆\emph{t}, the acceleration \emph{at} is selected
that minimizes the estimated \emph{C} (\emph{θt,} ∆\emph{t, at}).

Step 2: This acceleration \emph{at} is applied to the cart (i.e.
inserted in the dierence equation 41).

Step 3: Using the resulting values for \emph{θt}+1 and ∆\emph{t}+1, the
smallest value for \emph{C} (\emph{θt}+1\emph{,} ∆\emph{t}+1\emph{,
at}+1) obtainable by varying \emph{at}+1 is determined.

Step 4: This \emph{C}-value gets inserted in the right-hand side of Eq.
(44), and is used to render an updated target value for \emph{C}
(\emph{θt,} ∆\emph{t, at}).

Step 5: A stochastic gradient descent update (backpropagation pass) to
the feedforward net is made using this target value in combination with
the inputs\emph{θt}, ∆\emph{t}, and \emph{at}.

Step 6: The discrete time \emph{t} is replaced by \emph{t} + 1.

This iteration is continued until convergence to an estimate \emph{C}
(\emph{θ,} ∆\emph{, a}) is observed that manages to keep \emph{cosθ} at
values above 0\emph{.}8.
\end{quote}

