\begin{quote}
In section 18 we encountered an example of a renormalization ow: a
trans-formation of the parameters of a problem which leaves unchanged
the physical aspects of the problem which are considered of interest. Of
particular relevance in many branches of physics is the case where this
transformation reduces the number of parameters required to describe the
problem. By repeatedly applying such a course-graining renormalization
transformation, ever simpler descriptions emerge until a minimal
description is reached that can not be transformed fur-ther. The
following, rather trivial, example illustrates the concept.
\end{quote}

Consider a chain of \emph{N} conductors.

\begin{quote}
It doesn\textquotesingle t matter whether these are

hydraulic conductors or electric conductors. The only thing that matters
is that the current through the conductors is constant along the chain,
and that each conductor responds linearly: the current through the
conductor labeled \emph{i} equals the conductance \emph{σi} of this
conductor times the driving force across the conductor. We are
interested in the eective conductance \emph{σtot} accross the whole
