larger chains of conductors. Such networks that need to get applied
repeatedly, we will refer to as \textquotesingle kernel
nets\textquotesingle. The number of inputs of a kernel net is referred
to as the \textquotesingle kernel size\textquotesingle, and the width of
the kernel net is referred to as the \textquotesingle lter
depth\textquotesingle. The kernel net on the right has kernel size 2 and
lter depth 3. Chains of four conductors can be renormalized to a single
conductor by hierarchically applying this kernel net three times in
total (see gure below).

\includegraphics[width=3.19167in,height=4.75833in]{vertopal_a4c513063dc5459badc01054b1b787a4/media/image39.png}

For a data set obtained by selecting four input conductances, each
selected uniformly at random on the interval {[}0\emph{.}1\emph{,} 1),
we obtain the following crossplot between network-derived conductances
and exact conductances.
\end{quote}

48

\begin{quote}
\includegraphics[width=3.825in,height=3.475in]{vertopal_a4c513063dc5459badc01054b1b787a4/media/image40.png}

Note that this result is obtained using no more than three adjustable
weights (\emph{a}, \emph{b} and \emph{c}). Note also that we
don\textquotesingle t need to stop at chains of four. Using the same
three-parameter kernel net as building block, also chains of length
eight or sixteen (or any power of two) can be renormalized into a single
conductance.

We can even do better. In the diagram above depicting the
\emph{σtot}(\emph{σ}1\emph{, σ}2\emph{, σ}3\emph{, σ}4) renormalization
network, we observe a linear layer that feeds into another linear layer.
As discussed in section 4, such a double linear layer can be contracted
into a single linear layer. Below gure shows the result of this
contraction. The 18 weights of the linear layer on the right-hand side
can all be expressed in terms of the 12 weights of the double layer on
the left hand side.30However, the key point to note here is that by
taking the network architecture on the right as a given, and refraining
from prescribing any weights, a more powerful renormalization net is
achieved.

30As discussed in section 4, a matrix multiplication of the weights in
the double layer yield the weights for the contracted layer.
\end{quote}

49

\begin{quote}
\includegraphics[width=3.93889in,height=2.54444in]{vertopal_a4c513063dc5459badc01054b1b787a4/media/image41.png}

If we apply the same double-layer contraction to the full hierarchy of
the con-ductance renormalization network, we notice below repeat network
architecture emerging.

\includegraphics[width=4.57639in,height=2.66389in]{vertopal_a4c513063dc5459badc01054b1b787a4/media/image42.png}

This is the architecture of a convolutional net with kernel size 2 and
lter depth 3. Here the \textquotesingle lter depth\textquotesingle{} is
visible as the size of the clusters of ReLU\textquotesingle s, and the
\textquotesingle kernel size\textquotesingle{} is recognizable as the
amount of branching between clusters of ReLU\textquotesingle s. Notice
that following the contraction operation, the repeat unit (or kernel
net) takes the shape of a layer of 18 multipliers feeding two clusters
of 3 rectiers into a single cluster of 3 rectiers.

Other values for \textquotesingle kernel size\textquotesingle{} and
\textquotesingle lter depth\textquotesingle{} are feasible. Below
diagram depicts the architecture of a convolutional net with kernel size
3 and lter depth 2. In this diagram, the repeat unit consists of 12
multipliers.
\end{quote}

