\begin{quote}
Next to a number denoting kernel size and a number denoting lter depth,
renormalization architectures also carry a number denoting the shift
between applications of the repeat unit within a layer. All
renormalization architectures depicted above have stride 2: the same
network unit is repeatedly applied within a layer with shifts over two
ReLU clusters. A stride of two ensures a factor two reduction in network
width between subsequent layers.
\end{quote}

\begin{longtable}[]{@{}
  >{\raggedright\arraybackslash}p{(\columnwidth - 0\tabcolsep) * \real{1.0000}}@{}}
\toprule()
\begin{minipage}[b]{\linewidth}\raggedright
\begin{quote}
Exercise: Draw the renormalization architecture resulting from a kernel
size 4, lter depth 1, and stride 2.
\end{quote}
\end{minipage} \\
\midrule()
\endhead
\bottomrule()
\end{longtable}

\begin{quote}
The above renormalization nets are assumed to emerge by hierarchicaly
re-peating the same kernel net. So the number of independent weights in
the renormalization net is limited to the number of weights featuring in
the repeat unit. For kernel size \emph{k} and lter depth \emph{n}, the
number of weights featuring in the repeat unit equals \emph{n}2\emph{k}.
Convolutional nets generalize this conceptual framework by applying a
repeat unit within a layer, while avoiding repeat application of the
same unit across dierent layers. The result is that each layer can
incorporate \emph{n}2\emph{k} independent weights.

Eectively, convolutional nets take the shape of deep feedforward nets
that exploit two fundamental physical features: locality and
translational invariance. Locality is exploited by utilizing kernels of
limited size. Translational invariance is exploited by applying the same
kernel repeatedly across a wide data range.
\end{quote}

51

\begin{quote}
Convolutional nets have yielded spectacular successes in many practical
appli-cations, and they continue to enjoy great popularity among machine
learning practitioners. The most impressive successes have been obtained
in applications such as image recognition that involve 2D data
structures. In the next section we will discuss such higher-dimensional
convolutional feedforward nets.

